<p><strong>Sicilian Scheveningen Move by Move PDF</strong></p>
<p><strong>What is the Sicilian Scheveningen Defense?</strong></p>
<p>The Sicilian Scheveningen Defense (1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Bc4 a6) is a sharp opening characterized by Black's early ...d6 and ...e6 pawn moves, which prevent White from gaining control of the central squares. It is a popular choice for Black against 1. e4, and can lead to dynamic and complex positions.</p>
<p><strong>What are the Main Lines of the Scheveningen?</strong></p>
<p>There are several main lines in the Scheveningen Defense, including:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Sveshnikov Variation (7. Bg5):</strong> White immediately challenges Black's e6 pawn with the bishop on g5.</li>
<li><strong>Najdorf Variation (7. Be3):</strong> White develops the bishop to e3, preparing to fianchetto it on g5.</li>
<li><strong>Keres Attack (7. f4):</strong> White attacks Black's center with the pawn push f4.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>How to Play the White Side of the Scheveningen?</strong></p>
<p>As White, the goal is to secure control of the center and develop pieces actively. Common strategies include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Attacking Black's e6 pawn with Bg5 or f4</li>
<li>Developing the bishop on g5 to put pressure on Black's pawn structure and initiate an attack on the kingside</li>
<li>Fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on g2 to support the queenside</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>How to Play the Black Side of the Scheveningen?</strong></p>
<p>As Black, the goal is to defend the center and develop pieces securely. Key strategies include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Controlling the e5 square with the d6 pawn</li>
<li>Developing the knight to f6 to protect the e6 pawn</li>
<li>fianchettoing the light-squared bishop on b7 to counter White's bishop on g5</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Where Can I Find a Move-by-Move Analysis of the Scheveningen?</strong></p>
<p>There are numerous online and offline resources that provide move-by-move analyses of the Scheveningen Defense. One popular resource is the ChessBase opening database, which offers detailed annotations and variations for each move. Additionally, there are books and videos dedicated to the Scheveningen Defense, providing in-depth analysis and guidance for both sides.</p>